    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-11-29T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-11-29T22:00:00-05:00" n="265"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d265">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 Changsha/8: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-30T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 30, 1930—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 30—5:55 a.m<note n="22" xml:id="d265fn22">Telegram
                            in two sections.</note>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1015. The following telegram has been received from the Minister at Nanking:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“November 28, 5 p.m. Your telegram number 402, November 24, 11 a.m.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>I saw Wang today and asked about the Changsha claims which are now
                                in preparation. He stated he had not decided how to handle matter.
                                Has a representative at Changsha making an investigation. Said that
                                one question which faced him was that Changsha incident was not like
                                Nanking incident in that latter was caused by troops under
                                Government flag while Changsha damages were caused by troops in
                                rebellion. He thought international law did not hold Government
                                responsible for damages caused by rebellious soldiers. I said that
                                my information was that forces of the Nationalist Government had
                                retired from the city without making any defense, leaving the
                                foreigners at the mercy of the attackers; that it was only due to
                                the fact that we had a small gunboat there that very serious
                                situation resulting in death of a number of defenseless American
                                citizens had been prevented. I stated that I would report that the
                                matter was still under investigation by the Government. I told him
                                we would be willing to have the claims gone over by a joint
                                commission as was the case with the Nanking claims.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>With reference to the payments on the Nanking claims now overdue,
                                he asks that we give them a little more time as the treasury has
                                been depleted by the war and every effort was made by the <pb
                                    facs="0316" n="218" xml:id="pg_218"/> Ministry of Finance to get
                                where it could resume payments. He thought that in 3 or 4 months
                                payment would be resumed.”</item>
                        </list>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
